\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {12}{\ignorespaces Per-kernel transform application frequency across the Rodinia corpus. Rows represent the 22~Rodinia kernels; columns represent the six AST-level transforms. Cell values give the total number of times each transform was applied to files belonging to that kernel, aggregated across all augmentation levels and API variants. The distribution is highly non-uniform: multi-file kernels such as \texttt  {myocyte} (15 source files) and \texttt  {bptree} accumulate many SwapCondition applications, while smaller kernels (e.g., \texttt  {pathfinder}, \texttt  {hotspot}) show lower counts. ChangeFunctionNames applies to only two kernels (\texttt  {huffman}, \texttt  {streamcluster}).}}{33}{figure.12}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:transform-freq}{{12}{33}{Per-kernel transform application frequency across the Rodinia corpus. Rows represent the 22~Rodinia kernels; columns represent the six AST-level transforms. Cell values give the total number of times each transform was applied to files belonging to that kernel, aggregated across all augmentation levels and API variants. The distribution is highly non-uniform: multi-file kernels such as \texttt {myocyte} (15 source files) and \texttt {bptree} accumulate many SwapCondition applications, while smaller kernels (e.g., \texttt {pathfinder}, \texttt {hotspot}) show lower counts. ChangeFunctionNames applies to only two kernels (\texttt {huffman}, \texttt {streamcluster})}{figure.12}{}}
